  "prompt": "What is the sense of smell?",
  "response": "The sense of smell, or olfaction, is one of the five traditional senses that allows humans and other animals to detect and perceive odors and chemical molecules in the air. Here are key details about the sense of smell:\n\n1. Basic mechanism\n- Odor molecules enter the nose and bind to specialized receptors in the nasal cavity\n- These receptors send signals to the olfactory bulb in the brain\n- The brain interprets these signals as specific smells\n\n2. Biological importance\n- Helps detect potential food sources\n- Warns of dangerous substances like smoke or spoiled food\n- Plays a role in social communication and emotional responses\n- Contributes to taste perception\n\n3. Olfactory system components\n- Olfactory receptors in the nasal cavity\n- Olfactory nerves\n- Olfactory bulb in the brain\n- Olfactory cortex for processing smell information\n\n4. Characteristics\n- Humans can detect thousands of different odors\n- Smell is closely linked to memory and emotions\n- Sensitivity varies among individuals\n- Can be affected by age, health conditions, and genetic factors\n\n5. Unique features\n- Direct neural connection to brain regions\n- Ability to detect minute quantities of chemical substances\n- Quick response to environmental changes",
